<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in SoCal commercial stoves</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Burner Won't Light</h3>
        <p>Three causes in order of frequency: (1) failed igniter or spark module — no spark visible when attempting ignition; (2) clogged burner orifice — spark present but gas can't flow; (3) failed gas valve — gas not reaching the burner. Try removing the burner cap and grate and cleaning debris first. If the orifice hole appears blocked, a cleaning service may resolve it without parts replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Weak or Yellow Flame</h3>
        <p>A properly burning gas burner produces a blue flame with a defined cone. Yellow or orange flame indicates incomplete combustion — most commonly from a clogged or partially blocked burner orifice, or a burner cap misaligned after cleaning. A weak flame regardless of color suggests insufficient gas pressure reaching the burner, pointing to a partially failed gas valve.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Pilot Light Won't Stay Lit</h3>
        <p>Standing pilot systems on older commercial ranges use a thermocouple — a temperature sensor that detects the pilot flame and allows the main gas valve to stay open. When the thermocouple fails, the pilot lights but the main gas valve closes and the burner won't stay on. Thermocouple replacement is a $80–$150 repair. Don't bypass or tape the thermocouple — it's a safety device.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Burner Ignites Then Goes Out</h3>
        <p>On electronic ignition systems, this usually indicates the flame sensor (sometimes called a thermocouple or flame rod depending on the system) isn't detecting the flame and cutting off the gas valve. The flame starts, the valve opens, then closes when the sensor doesn't confirm sustained combustion. Sensor cleaning or replacement resolves this in most cases.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Uneven Heat / One Section Not Working</h3>
        <p>On a multi-section range (6-burner, 8-burner), one side or section not lighting while others work normally usually indicates a zone gas valve failure rather than individual burner issues. Zone valves control multiple burners; when a zone valve fails, all burners in that zone go down together. Useful diagnostic: if all three left burners fail simultaneously, it's likely a zone valve, not three separate igniter failures.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Griddle Temperature Inconsistent</h3>
        <p>Commercial griddle thermostat drift — the thermostat controls griddle surface temperature and wears out over time. A griddle showing 350°F but cooking inconsistently at 300°F or 420°F has a drifted or failing thermostat. We calibrate against a calibrated probe before condemning the thermostat, since sometimes the display is inaccurate rather than the heating system itself.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

