<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Chinatown · Chinese Restaurant · American Range Wok Range (3-Burner)</div>
        <h3>"Two wok burners won't light — carbon buildup, orifice completely blocked"</h3>
        <p>Clogged wok ring orifice jets on two of three burners of an American Range wok range running 150,000 BTU per burner. The orifice jets on high-BTU wok burners accumulate carbon at a much faster rate than standard commercial burners — the intense heat conditions and wok cooking technique (sauce and oil splashing directly into the flame) builds carbon deposits in the jet orifice over months.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed and cleaned all three wok ring assemblies with commercial carbon solvent — orifice jets on two burners were completely blocked. Tested all three burners through multiple ignition cycles after cleaning — full blue flame within spec on all three. Advised on monthly orifice cleaning as part of kitchen cleaning routine. Third burner had a weakening igniter (still lighting but taking 3–4 attempts) — replaced proactively on same visit to prevent a service call within months. Full service: $195 including diagnostic.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (OC) · Coastal Steakhouse · Garland G60-6T Gas Range</div>
        <h3>"Left side three burners completely dead — right side works fine"</h3>
        <p>Zone gas valve failure on a Garland 6-burner range at a Newport Beach steakhouse — the valve controlling the left-side burner zone had failed closed, cutting off gas to all three left burners simultaneously. Classic zone valve failure presentation: three burners go down at the same time rather than one. The restaurant had been running dinner service using only the right three burners, slowing their line and affecting ticket times.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Diagnosed zone valve failure by verifying spark function on all three left burners (sparks present, confirming igniters functional) and testing gas pressure downstream of the valve (none). Replaced zone valve assembly with OEM Garland part. All six burners operational within 90 minutes of arrival. Tested BTU output on all burners against Garland spec. Calibrated charbroiler radiants on adjacent unit while there — found one with corroded gas inlet. Restaurant back to full line capacity for evening service.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Westlake Village (Ventura) · American Bistro · Vulcan V6B Range</div>
        <h3>"One burner ignites but goes out after 5 seconds"</h3>
        <p>Failed flame sensor on a Vulcan V6B electronic ignition range at a Westlake Village bistro — the flame rod (a probe that detects the presence of flame and holds the gas valve open) had corroded and was no longer producing adequate ionization current to signal the control board. The burner would ignite, the control board would check for flame confirmation, fail to detect it, and cut the gas valve — all within a few seconds.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Identified flame rod failure by measuring ionization current with a microamp meter — reading 0.2 µA vs the 1.5 µA minimum for reliable valve hold-in. Replaced flame rod. Tested through 10 full ignition cycles — flame rod reading 3.8 µA, consistent valve hold-in. Also cleaned burner cap and orifice on the affected burner which had visible grease buildup contributing to inconsistent flame geometry. Total repair: $165 including diagnostic.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown · Korean BBQ Restaurant · Imperial Range IR-6</div>
        <h3>"Pilot light keeps going out — burners won't stay lit"</h3>
        <p>Failed thermocouple on a standing-pilot Imperial range — the thermocouple generates a small millivolt signal when heated by the pilot flame, which holds the main gas safety valve open. When the thermocouple fails, the valve defaults closed (the safe state), and no burners will ignite or stay on. The restaurant had been relighting the pilot every 30–45 minutes until it stopped staying lit at all.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Measured thermocouple millivolt output — reading 8 mV vs the 18–20 mV required to hold the safety valve open. Replaced thermocouple. Pilot stayed lit on first attempt after replacement. Verified main burner operation on all 6 positions. Also cleaned pilot orifice which had partial blockage contributing to pilot instability. Explained thermocouple function to kitchen manager — next time it goes out temporarily, it's the pilot orifice; won't stay lit at all, it's the thermocouple. Took 5 minutes but will save them a confused phone call in the future.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

