<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">09 — Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Commercial stove repair — what SoCal operators ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does commercial stove repair cost?</h3>
        <p>Commercial diagnostic is $120, applied to repair if approved. Most repairs run $150–$500. Igniter, thermocouple, gas valve, orifice cleaning, or flame sensor is in this range. Zone valve work runs higher. Written estimate before any work begins.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Which areas of Southern California do you cover for commercial stove repair?</h3>
        <p>Same-day across <strong>Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties</strong> — Koreatown and Chinatown LA wok ranges, San Gabriel Valley Chinese restaurants, Anaheim and Garden Grove OC Korean/Vietnamese kitchens, Thousand Oaks Conejo Valley restaurants, Rancho Cucamonga and Riverside IE foodservice. Eight service territories total. Vulcan, Garland, Southbend, Imperial — gas-certified across the entire footprint. BHGS Licensed #A49573.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My commercial gas stove smells like gas — what do I do?</h3>
        <p>Call your gas utility first — SoCalGas at 1-800-427-2200 across most of LA, OC, Ventura, and parts of SB; Southwest Gas at 1-877-860-6020 for Riverside, Anaheim, Long Beach, and parts of SB. They'll shut off gas safely at no charge and confirm the area is clear. Then call us at {phone} for the mechanical repair. Gas utility first, appliance repair second.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My commercial burner won't light — what should I check first?</h3>
        <p>Remove the burner cap and grate and check for debris or carbon buildup in the burner orifice hole. A clogged orifice is the most common cause and cleans up in minutes. If the orifice is clear and there's no spark, that's an igniter. If there's a spark but no flame, that's a gas valve or clogged orifice.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair wok ranges and high-BTU commercial ranges?</h3>
        <p>Yes. High-BTU wok ranges (75,000–200,000 BTU/burner) are a significant part of our SoCal service calls — LA's Chinatown/Koreatown/SGV, OC's Anaheim/Garden Grove, IE's Asian foodservice clusters. When you call, mention "wok range" so we bring the appropriate parts and tools.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What's the difference between commercial stove and oven repair?</h3>
        <p>Stove repair covers the open-burner cooking surface — igniters, gas valves, thermocouples, orifices. Oven repair covers the enclosed cooking chamber — heating elements, convection fans, deck oven systems. Most commercial ranges have both; we repair both on the same visit when needed. See our <a href="/commercial/oven-repair/" style="color:var(--red);">Commercial Oven Repair page</a> for oven-specific issues.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair Vulcan, Garland, and Southbend commercial ranges?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Vulcan, Garland, Southbend, Imperial, and Montague are our most common SoCal service brands. Parts for Vulcan and Garland carried on service vehicles; others sourced same-day.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>When does it make sense to repair vs replace a commercial range?</h3>
        <p>Commercial ranges last 12–20+ years with proper maintenance. Repair almost always wins. New 6-burner Vulcan or Garland ranges run $4,000–$9,000+; high-BTU wok ranges $6,000–$15,000+; charbroilers $3,000–$7,000. A $400–$700 zone valve replacement on a $7,000 range with another decade of life is straightforward math. We tell you directly when a unit has reached end-of-life — usually only after a full burner-bank gas-valve assembly fails on a unit already 20+ years old.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

